docs.text: Photograph by Simeon Boschoff C -lang B ehaviour T able Documenting various compiler implementations' of unspecified behaviour in C programs This website contains code examples of C code that uses unspecified C language features that behave in different ways depending on the compiler used and possibly the flags used during compilation as well. Sections There are several main sections that look at parts of the C specification which are unspecified. The main sections are listed in the navigation bar above.

docs.text: B1 : Binary operator test Description The order in which the operands, the left-hand side expression and the right-hand side expression, of a binary operator expression are executed is underspecified. int j = count(1) + count(2); Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int counter = 0; int arr[2] = {0,0}; int count(int i) { counter = counter + 1; arr[i-1] = counter; return 0; } int main() { int j = count(1) + count(2); assert(arr[0] == 1); assert(arr[1] == 2); j++; return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 2 && result[1] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 ( result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 ) Running program: binop/bop1/test_lr.c #include<assert.h> int counter = 0; int arr[2] = {0,0}; int count(int i) { counter = counter + 1; arr[i-1] = counter; return 0; } int main() { int j = count(1) + count(2); assert(arr[0] == 1); assert(arr[1] == 2); j++; return 0; } Expected assertion: result[0] == 1 && docs.title: B1

docs.text: The order in which the operands, the left-hand side expression and the right-hand side expression, of a binary operator expression are executed is underspecified. int j = count(1) + count(2);
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int counter = 0; int arr[2] = {0,0}; int count(int i) { counter = counter + 1; arr[i-1] = counter; return 0; } int main() { int j = count(1) + count(2); assert(arr[0] == 1); assert(arr[1] == 2); j++; return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 2 && result[1] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.text: C2 : Test function call and comma operator This test, like C1 , will also test the ordering of evaluation and a function call within. So we are checking to see the following: Ordering of execution of comma-operator list items The function-call's arguments evaluation ordering The test we will be looking at is below: int result = (updateX(1), f)(updateX(2), updateX(3)); Now it is already specificed in the C specification that we should execute updateX(1) and then handle f(..1, ..2) with its arguments (and their order being something found in the F* tests). We are just doing these comma-operator tests for sanity checking to make sure nobody actually does try and go against the specification. Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int result = (updateX(1), f)(updateX(2), updateX(3)); // assert(map[0] == 1); // assert(map[1] == 2); // assert(map[2] == 3); // assert(result == 7); return 0; } Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. result=f(2,3) */ assert(map[0] == 1); assert(map[1] == 2); assert(map[2] == 3); assert(result == 7); return 0; } Expected assertion: comma-operator ltr (spec), func. args. ltr (unspec) Verifier (unspec) ❌️ 96c334b1475a6d6ee71834eb57862ae8 Analysis As we can see, function call evaluation ordering aside (which is what the first two test results show), the specification of the comma-operator is infact enforced. The last two tests which seek to see the ordering of the comma-operator not enforced, i.e. the first expression in the "tuple" appears to be executed last, show that the specification is indeed enforced and no compiler orders the comman operator differently. Explicit versions To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. Just for the sake of the clarity I added explicit versions for both permutations caused by F* behaviour in the function call arguments, but both enforce the correct left-to-right execution ordering of the expression evaluation in the comma-operator operand expressions. comma-operator ltr (spec), func. args. ltr (unspec) #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int res1 = updateX(1); int res2 = updateX(2); int res3 = updateX(3); int result = (res1, f)(res2, res3); /* 1, f(2, 3) with result=f(2,3) */ assert(map[0] == 1); assert(map[1] == 2); assert(map[2] == 3); assert(result == 7); return 0; } comma-operator ltr (spec), func. args. rtl (unspec) #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int res1 = updateX(1); int res2 = updateX(3); int res3 = updateX(2); int result = (res1, f)(res3, res2); /* 1, f(3, 2) with result=f(3,2) */ assert(map[0] == 1); assert(map[1] == 3); assert(map[2] == 2); assert(result == 7); return 0; }
docs.title: C2

docs.text: This test, like C1 , will also test the ordering of evaluation and a function call within. So we are checking to see the following: Ordering of execution of comma-operator list items The function-call's arguments evaluation ordering The test we will be looking at is below: int result = (updateX(1), f)(updateX(2), updateX(3)); Now it is already specificed in the C specification that we should execute updateX(1) and then handle f(..1, ..2) with its arguments (and their order being something found in the F* tests). We are just doing these comma-operator tests for sanity checking to make sure nobody actually does try and go against the specification.
docs.title: C2: Test function call and comma operator

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int result = (updateX(1), f)(updateX(2), updateX(3)); // assert(map[0] == 1); // assert(map[1] == 2); // assert(map[2] == 3); // assert(result == 7); return 0; }

docs.text: As we can see, function call evaluation ordering aside (which is what the first two test results show), the specification of the comma-operator is infact enforced. The last two tests which seek to see the ordering of the comma-operator not enforced, i.e. the first expression in the "tuple" appears to be executed last, show that the specification is indeed enforced and no compiler orders the comman operator differently.
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. Just for the sake of the clarity I added explicit versions for both permutations caused by F* behaviour in the function call arguments, but both enforce the correct left-to-right execution ordering of the expression evaluation in the comma-operator operand expressions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int res1 = updateX(1); int res2 = updateX(2); int res3 = updateX(3); int result = (res1, f)(res2, res3); /* 1, f(2, 3) with result=f(2,3) */ assert(map[0] == 1); assert(map[1] == 2); assert(map[2] == 3); assert(result == 7); return 0; }

docs.text: #include<assert.h> int map[3] = {0,0,0}; int x = 0; int id = 0; int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int updateX(int sig) { map[id] = sig; id++; x++; return x; } int main() { int res1 = updateX(1); int res2 = updateX(3); int res3 = updateX(2); int result = (res1, f)(res3, res2); /* 1, f(3, 2) with result=f(3,2) */ assert(map[0] == 1); assert(map[1] == 3); assert(map[2] == 2); assert(result == 7); return 0; }

docs.text: Comma operator The comma-operator is meant to enforce the sequencing of expressions, from left-to-right and then retruning the result of the last executed expression - which would be the right-most one. An example of this would be: int result = (f1(), f2(), f3()); This code, by specification, should execute the argument list in the order of f1() , f2() and then lastly f3() and return the result of f3() as the value of the expression (.., .., ..) . Why test it if it is not unspecified? We may as well, you never know how some compilers can behave, we may as well make sure. Also, we don't know what the verifiers are accounting for possibly, so let's test it anyways.
docs.title: Introduction

docs.text: F1 : Function Call Evaluation ordering Description The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the outer function's arguments are evaluated with an outer function that is sensitive to which argument is which value and with an inner function which depends on global state such that each successive call results in a different result but a determinable one: int result = f(counter(), counter()); F1 is a very basic test with the same inner-function, counter() , being used as the outer function's, f(__arg1__, __arg2__) , arguments (only 2 arguments). Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int result = f(counter(), counter()); //assert(result == 4); //assert(result == 5); } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result == 4 This implies left-to-right evaluation result == 5 This implies right-to-left evaluation Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 ( result == 4 ) Running program: functions/f1/program_analysis.c #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int result = f(counter(), counter()); assert(result == 4); return 0; } Expected assertion: result == 4 Explicit versions To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. right-to-left execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int arg2 = counter(); int arg1 = counter(); int result = f(arg1, arg2); assert(result == 5); } left-to-right execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int arg1 = counter(); int arg2 = counter(); int result = f(arg1, arg2); assert(result == 4); }
docs.title: F1

docs.text: The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the outer function's arguments are evaluated with an outer function that is sensitive to which argument is which value and with an inner function which depends on global state such that each successive call results in a different result but a determinable one: int result = f(counter(), counter()); F1 is a very basic test with the same inner-function, counter() , being used as the outer function's, f(__arg1__, __arg2__) , arguments (only 2 arguments).
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int result = f(counter(), counter()); //assert(result == 4); //assert(result == 5); } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result == 4 This implies left-to-right evaluation result == 5 This implies right-to-left evaluation
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.text: Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test:
docs.title: Results of behaviour

docs.text: There is definetly a difference, gcc seems to ALWAYS , prefer right-to-left. Every other compiler, prefers left-to-right .
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2) { return (x1*2)+x2; } int main() { int arg2 = counter(); int arg1 = counter(); int result = f(arg1, arg2); assert(result == 5); }

docs.title: left-to-right execution ordering

docs.text: F2 : Function Call Evaluation ordering Description The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the outer function's arguments are evaluated with an outer function that is sensitive to which argument is which value and with an inner function which depends on global state such that each successive call results in a different result but a determinable one: f(counter(), counter(), counter()); F2 will use a different testing mechanism as simply cloning F1 can return results which give the same number for more than ordering, therefore we will be using an array which has inherent order, to store the arguments passed to the function f(__arg1__, __arg2__, __arg3__) . Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { f(counter(), counter(), counter()); /** * assert(orderArray[0] == 3); * assert(orderArray[1] == 2); * assert(orderArray[2] == 1); */ /** * assert(orderArray[0] == 1); * assert(orderArray[1] == 2); * assert(orderArray[2] == 3); */ return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): orderArray[0] == 3 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 1 : The implies right-to-left ordering orderArray[0] == 1 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 3 : The implies left-to-right ordering Although there could be 3! orderings, from testing you will see there are only two as the assertion failures and passes are mutually exclusive with each other Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 ( orderArray[0] == 1 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 3 ) Running program: functions/f2/program_analysis.c #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { f(counter(), counter(), counter()); assert(orderArray[0] == 1); assert(orderArray[1] == 2); assert(orderArray[2] == 3); return 0; } Expected assertion: orderArray[0] Every other compiler, prefers left-to-right . Explicit versions To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. right-to-left execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { int arg1 = counter(); int arg2 = counter(); int arg3 = counter(); f(arg3, arg2, arg1); assert(orderArray[0] == 3); assert(orderArray[1] == 2); assert(orderArray[2] == 1); return 0; } left-to-right execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { int arg1 = counter(); int arg2 = counter(); int arg3 = counter(); f(arg1, arg2, arg3); assert(orderArray[0] == 1); assert(orderArray[1] == 2); assert(orderArray[2] == 3); return 0; }
docs.title: F2

docs.text: The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the outer function's arguments are evaluated with an outer function that is sensitive to which argument is which value and with an inner function which depends on global state such that each successive call results in a different result but a determinable one: f(counter(), counter(), counter()); F2 will use a different testing mechanism as simply cloning F1 can return results which give the same number for more than ordering, therefore we will be using an array which has inherent order, to store the arguments passed to the function f(__arg1__, __arg2__, __arg3__) .
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { f(counter(), counter(), counter()); /** * assert(orderArray[0] == 3); * assert(orderArray[1] == 2); * assert(orderArray[2] == 1); */ /** * assert(orderArray[0] == 1); * assert(orderArray[1] == 2); * assert(orderArray[2] == 3); */ return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): orderArray[0] == 3 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 1 : The implies right-to-left ordering orderArray[0] == 1 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 3 : The implies left-to-right ordering Although there could be 3! orderings, from testing you will see there are only two as the assertion failures and passes are mutually exclusive with each other
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.title: Program 2 (orderArray[0] == 3 && orderArray[1] == 2 && orderArray[2] == 1)

docs.text: There is definetly a difference, gcc seems to ALWAYS , prefer right-to-left . Every other compiler, prefers left-to-right .
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { int arg1 = counter(); int arg2 = counter(); int arg3 = counter(); f(arg3, arg2, arg1); assert(orderArray[0] == 3); assert(orderArray[1] == 2); assert(orderArray[2] == 1); return 0; }
docs.title: right-to-left execution ordering

docs.text: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } char orderArray[3] = {0,0,0}; void f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { orderArray[0] = x1; orderArray[1] = x2; orderArray[2] = x3; } int main() { int arg1 = counter(); int arg2 = counter(); int arg3 = counter(); f(arg1, arg2, arg3); assert(orderArray[0] == 1); assert(orderArray[1] == 2); assert(orderArray[2] == 3); return 0; }
docs.title: left-to-right execution ordering

docs.text: F2 : Function Call Evaluation ordering (3 args) Description The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which these funtions are executed by using globally shared state with funcitons senstiive to that. int result = f(counter(), counter(), counter()); F2 is simply F1 but with three arguments. Implicit version The implicit version of what we will be analysing is related to the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { return (x1*2)+x2+x3*3; } int main() { /** * 1,2,3 => (1*2)+2+3*3 => 13 * 3,2,1 => (3*2)+2+1*3 => 11 */ int result = f(counter(), counter(), counter()); printf("%d\n", result); } Results of behaviour Here we document the behaviour of various C compiler implementations on the above code and which arguments (further variations) were used and lastly the outcome. Every compiler and options combination that has a certain obersavtion is matched below: right-to-left execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { return (x1*2)+x2+x3*3; } int main() { /** * 1,2,3 => (1*2)+2+3*3 => 13 * 3,2,1 => (3*2)+2+1*3 => 11 */ int subRes1 = counter(); int subRes2 = counter(); int subRes3 = counter(); int result = f(subRes3, subRes2, subRes1); assert(result == 11); } left-to-right execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { return (x1*2)+x2+x3*3; } int main() { /** * 1,2,3 => (1*2)+2+3*3 => 13 * 3,2,1 => (3*2)+2+1*3 => 11 */ int subRes1 = counter(); int subRes2 = counter(); int subRes3 = counter(); int result = f(subRes1, subRes2, subRes3); assert(result == 13); }
docs.title: F2 3args
F2: Function Call Evaluation ordering (3 args)

docs.text: The order in which the arguments to a function is evaluated is unspeccified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which these funtions are executed by using globally shared state with funcitons senstiive to that. int result = f(counter(), counter(), counter()); F2 is simply F1 but with three arguments.
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of what we will be analysing is related to the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> int globalCounter = 0; int counter() { globalCounter++; return globalCounter; } int f(int x1, int x2, int x3) { return (x1*2)+x2+x3*3; } int main() { /** * 1,2,3 => (1*2)+2+3*3 => 13 * 3,2,1 => (3*2)+2+1*3 => 11 */ int result = f(counter(), counter(), counter()); printf("%d\n", result); }

docs.text: F69 : Level-order test for function evaluation Description Tests f1 and F2 have demonstrated clearly that strict left-to-right and right-to-left behaviour is adhered to in simple cases whereby there are no nested function calls in the expressions that make up the arguments to the outer function calls. What this test case aims to show is that the ordering is not only strictly left-to-right or right-to-left but also that it is for when one does nested calls and that the logic of sequence points applies still. Really it just reassures us the logic holds. See the code below to get a concrete understanding of the behaviour we are looking to analyse by reading the assertions that are assrting a certain SPECIFIC ordering. Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 ( left to right strict ) Running program: functions/f69/recursive_lr.c #include<assert.h> char order[5] = {0,0,0,0,0}; int counter = 0; int getCount() { counter = counter + 1; return counter; } int func(int x1, int x2) { order[4] = getCount(); return 0; } int gunc(int x1, int x2) { order[2] = getCount(); return 144; } int f1() { order[0] = getCount(); return 4; } int f2() { order[1] = getCount(); return 55; } int f3() { order[3] = getCount(); return 67; } int main() { func(gunc(f1(), f2()), f3()); /* Left to right */ assert(order[0] == 1); assert(order[1] == 2); assert(order[2] == 3); assert(order[3] == 4); assert(order[4] == 5); return 0; } Expected assertion: left to right Verifier Arguments Assertion expected Assertion result docs.title: F69
F69: Level-order test for function evaluation

docs.text: Tests f1 and F2 have demonstrated clearly that strict left-to-right and right-to-left behaviour is adhered to in simple cases whereby there are no nested function calls in the expressions that make up the arguments to the outer function calls. What this test case aims to show is that the ordering is not only strictly left-to-right or right-to-left but also that it is for when one does nested calls and that the logic of sequence points applies still. Really it just reassures us the logic holds. See the code below to get a concrete understanding of the behaviour we are looking to analyse by reading the assertions that are assrting a certain SPECIFIC ordering.
docs.title: Description

docs.text: Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test:
docs.title: Results of behaviour

x2) { order[4] = getCount(); return 0; } int gunc(int x1, int x2) { order[2] = getCount(); return 144; } int f1() { order[0] = getCount(); return 4; } int f2() { order[1] = getCount(); return 55; } int f3() { order[3] = getCount(); return 67; } int main() { func(gunc(f1(), f2()), f3()); /* Left to right */ assert(order[0] == 1); assert(order[1] == 2); assert(order[2] == 3); assert(order[3] == docs.title: Program 2 (right to left strict)

docs.text: L1 : List initializer element evaluation ordering Description The order in which the elements in a list initializer are evaluated is unspecified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the elements in the list initializer are evaluated. Seeing that there is implicit order in an array we will be able to see if the evaluation order differs by the placement of returned results in the array: int result[2] = {counter(), counter()}; L1 is very basic, we are using only two elements in the initializer for result[2] and also the same funciton is being used, counter() , as the element initializer. Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { /** * Calculate the array * * Ex1: {1, 2} * Ex2: {2, 1} */ int result[2] = {counter(), counter()}; /** * assert(result[0] == 1); * assert(result[1] == 2); */ /** * assert(result[0] == 2); * assert(result[1] == 1); */ } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 2 && result[1] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 ( result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 ) Running program: lists/l1/program_analysis.c #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { /** * Calculate the array * * Ex1: {1, 2} * Ex2: {2, 1} */ int result[2] = {counter(), counter()}; assert(result[0] == 1); assert(result[1] == 2); return 0; } Expected assertion: result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 Verifier Arguments Assertion expected Assertion result Job hash CBMC ['cbmc'] result[0] Explicit versions To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. right-to-left execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int res1_val = counter(); int res2_val = counter(); int result[2] = {res2_val, res1_val}; assert(result[0] == 2); assert(result[1] == 1); } left-to-right execution ordering #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int res1_val = counter(); int res2_val = counter(); int result[2] = {res1_val, res2_val}; assert(result[0] == 1); assert(result[1] == 2); }
docs.title: L1
L1: List initializer element evaluation ordering

docs.text: The order in which the elements in a list initializer are evaluated is unspecified. Here we will be looking at a piece of code which results in different outcomes depending on the order in which the elements in the list initializer are evaluated. Seeing that there is implicit order in an array we will be able to see if the evaluation order differs by the placement of returned results in the array: int result[2] = {counter(), counter()}; L1 is very basic, we are using only two elements in the initializer for result[2] and also the same funciton is being used, counter() , as the element initializer.
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { /** * Calculate the array * * Ex1: {1, 2} * Ex2: {2, 1} */ int result[2] = {counter(), counter()}; /** * assert(result[0] == 1); * assert(result[1] == 2); */ /** * assert(result[0] == 2); * assert(result[1] == 1); */ } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 2 && result[1] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.text: Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test:
docs.title: Results of behaviour

docs.text: Every compiler always does left-to-right evaluation.
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int res1_val = counter(); int res2_val = counter(); int result[2] = {res2_val, res1_val}; assert(result[0] == 2); assert(result[1] == 1); }
docs.title: right-to-left execution ordering

docs.text: #include<assert.h> #include<stdio.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int res1_val = counter(); int res2_val = counter(); int result[2] = {res1_val, res2_val}; assert(result[0] == 1); assert(result[1] == 2); }
docs.title: left-to-right execution ordering

docs.text: L2 : List initializer (with 3 elements) Description This test is like that of L2 but that we will use three elements instead: int result[3] = {counter(), counter(), counter()}; Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { /** * Calculate the array * * Ex1: {1, 2, 3} */ int result[3] = {counter(), counter(), counter()}; /** * assert(result[0] == 1); * assert(result[1] == 2); * assert(result[2] == 3); */ /** * assert(result[0] == 3); * assert(result[1] == 2); * assert(result[2] == 1); */ return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two (you will see that these are the only ones that actually occur, not 3!) possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 && result[2] == 3 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 3 && result[1] == 2 && result[2] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. docs.title: L2

docs.text: This test is like that of L2 but that we will use three elements instead: int result[3] = {counter(), counter(), counter()};
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { /** * Calculate the array * * Ex1: {1, 2, 3} */ int result[3] = {counter(), counter(), counter()}; /** * assert(result[0] == 1); * assert(result[1] == 2); * assert(result[2] == 3); */ /** * assert(result[0] == 3); * assert(result[1] == 2); * assert(result[2] == 1); */ return 0; } We will be testing a two versions of this same program to account for the two (you will see that these are the only ones that actually occur, not 3!) possible outcomes (and also what they mean semantically): result[0] == 1 && result[1] == 2 && result[2] == 3 This implies left-to-right evaluation result[0] == 3 && result[1] == 2 && result[2] == 1 This implies right-to-left evaluation
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.title: Results of behaviour

docs.text: Every compiler always does left-to-right evaluation.
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> /* Global data */ int count = 0; /* Counting function */ int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int res1_val = counter(); int res2_val = counter(); int res3_val = counter(); int result[3] = {res1_val, res2_val, res3_val}; assert(result[0] == 1); assert(result[1] == 2); assert(result[2] == 3); return 0; }
docs.title: left-to-right execution ordering

docs.text: L3 : Multi-dimensional list initializer evaluation ordering Description The order of which the elements of a list is initialized has already been stated to be unspecified and we have done many-a-test to see what ordering compilers (under various modes) choose to use for them. We haven't, however, looked at the ordering of multi-dimensional arrays, this is just a quick test to confirm results possibly. Therefore we will be looking at the behaviour of the following code: int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()} }; Implicit version The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int count = 0; int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()} }; assert(arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1); assert(arrayOfArrays[0][1] == 2); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][0] == 3); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][1] == 4); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][0] == 5); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][1] == 6); return 0; } We will be seeing whether it does row-major initialization, meaning it initializes each row first and then what ordering within each list-initializer ( {counter(), counter()} ) it decides to use. This is opposed to column-major which would go down each list and initialize the first element in each, then go down each list again and initialize the second element of each. Results of behaviour Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test: Program 1 (row-major left-to-right) Running program: lists/l3/program_analysis.c #include<assert.h> int count = 0; int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()} }; assert(arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1); assert(arrayOfArrays[0][1] == 2); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][0] == 3); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][1] == 4); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][0] == 5); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][1] == 6); return 0; } Expected assertion: arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1 && ❌️ 96c334b1475a6d6ee71834eb57862ae8 Analysis It would appear all compilers and software verifiers do row-major left-to-right execution ordering when initializing multi-dimensional arrays. Explicit versions To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions. row-major left-to-right execution ordering #include<assert.h> int count = 0; int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int c1 = counter(); int c2 = counter(); int c3 = counter(); int c4 = counter(); int c5 = counter(); int c6 = counter(); int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {c1, c2}, {c3, c4}, {c5, c6} }; assert(arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1); assert(arrayOfArrays[0][1] == 2); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][0] == 3); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][1] == 4); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][0] == 5); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][1] == 6); return 0; }
docs.title: L3
L3: Multi-dimensional list initializer evaluation ordering

docs.text: The order of which the elements of a list is initialized has already been stated to be unspecified and we have done many-a-test to see what ordering compilers (under various modes) choose to use for them. We haven't, however, looked at the ordering of multi-dimensional arrays, this is just a quick test to confirm results possibly. Therefore we will be looking at the behaviour of the following code: int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()} };
docs.title: Description

docs.text: The implicit version of the program will be the following: #include<assert.h> int count = 0; int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()}, {counter(), counter()} }; assert(arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1); assert(arrayOfArrays[0][1] == 2); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][0] == 3); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][1] == 4); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][0] == 5); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][1] == 6); return 0; } We will be seeing whether it does row-major initialization, meaning it initializes each row first and then what ordering within each list-initializer ( {counter(), counter()} ) it decides to use. This is opposed to column-major which would go down each list and initialize the first element in each, then go down each list again and initialize the second element of each.
docs.title: Implicit version

docs.text: Here we test several different compilers and software verifiers and several flags and C standards per each. We will be testing two versions in this test:

docs.title: Program 2 (column-major top-to-bottom)

docs.text: It would appear all compilers and software verifiers do row-major left-to-right execution ordering when initializing multi-dimensional arrays.
docs.title: Analysis

docs.text: To improve CSeq per-compiler behaviour we will need explicit versions that provide the given behaviour, in this case there will be only two explicit versions.
docs.title: Explicit versions

docs.text: #include<assert.h> int count = 0; int counter() { count++; return count; } int main() { int c1 = counter(); int c2 = counter(); int c3 = counter(); int c4 = counter(); int c5 = counter(); int c6 = counter(); int arrayOfArrays[3][2] = { {c1, c2}, {c3, c4}, {c5, c6} }; assert(arrayOfArrays[0][0] == 1); assert(arrayOfArrays[0][1] == 2); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][0] == 3); assert(arrayOfArrays[1][1] == 4); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][0] == 5); assert(arrayOfArrays[2][1] == 6); return 0; }
docs.title: row-major left-to-right execution ordering

docs.text: Lists What is this section about? This section is aimed at documenting the behaviour of so called "list initialzers" in C. This is a language feature ( TODO : Find out when this was added (which specificaiton version)) which allows one to initialize the elements of an array as part of the array declaration. An example may be the following: /** * Initialize an array to have the values of [0, 1, 2]: */ int array[3] = {0, 1, 2}; Rules The example provided above is a very basic example and the behaviour of it is the same across implementations for the simple reason that the values used to initialize it, namely 0 , 1 and 2 , require no further evaluation. Where the focus of this section comes in is when these expressions are more complex, specifically with expressions that have side-effects and where those side-effects effect the returned value of the evaluation. We will therefore be looking therefore at code that is more along the lines of the following: /** * Initialize the array to have the first element be the returned value of `f()` * and the second element the returned value of `g()` */ int array[2] = {f(), g()}; Unspecified behaviour One would assume that the order of evaluation would be to call f() then g() and have those returned values respectively saved into the positions, array[0] and array[1] . The latter happens, but the former (the order of calls) is unspecified and the order of execution is up to the compiler implementer. Table of behaviour This section contains several tables relating to how a specific snippet of C code, which makes use of this undeterminism, behaves. 2-argument function call TODO
